COMPMS.title: Manufacturing Sector: Hourly Compensation for All Employed Persons
COMPMS.notes:
Effective February 5, 2004, Productivity and Cost measures for the manufacturing sector
are now reported using the 2002 North American Industry Classification System (NAICS).
Because of the reclassification, these measures are not directly comparable with
manufacturing measures published on or before Dec. 3, 2003.

For further information, please visit the Bureau Of Labor Statistics web
site at https://www.bls.gov/lpc/

IPUEN311L000000000.title: Labor Productivity for Manufacturing: Food Manufacturing (NAICS 311) in the United States
IPUEN311L000000000.notes: Labor productivity describes the efficiency at which labor hours are utilized in producing output of goods and services, measured as output per hour of labor.

IPUEN311L010000000.title: Hours Worked for Manufacturing: Food Manufacturing (NAICS 311) in the United States
IPUEN311L010000000.notes: Labor hours are measured as annual hours worked by all workers, including wage and salary workers, unincorporated self-employed workers, and unpaid family workers, in the production of goods and services.

IPUEN311L020000000.title: Labor Compensation for Manufacturing: Food Manufacturing (NAICS 311) in the United States
IPUEN311L020000000.notes: Labor compensation, defined as payroll plus supplemental payments, is a measure of the cost to the employer of securing the services of labor. Payroll includes salaries, wages, commissions, dismissal pay, bonuses, vacation and sick leave pay, and compensation in kind. Supplemental payments include both legally required expenditures and payments for voluntary programs. The legally required portion consists primarily of federal old age and survivors’ insurance, unemployment compensation, and workers’ compensation. Payments for voluntary programs include all programs not specifically required by legislation, such as the employer portion of private health insurance and pension plans.

IPUEN311U100000000.title: Unit Labor Costs for Manufacturing: Food Manufacturing (NAICS 311) in the United States
IPUEN311U100000000.notes: Unit labor costs represent the cost of labor required to produce one unit of output. The unit labor cost indexes are computed by dividing an index of nominal industry labor compensation by an index of real industry output.

IPUEN311U110000000.title: Labor Compensation for Manufacturing: Food Manufacturing (NAICS 311) in the United States

IPUEN311U120000000.title: Hourly Compensation for Manufacturing: Food Manufacturing (NAICS 311) in the United States
IPUEN311U120000000.notes: Hourly compensation is the sum of wage and salary accruals and supplements to wages and salaries per hour of labor services used to produce output. Wage and salary accruals consist of the monetary remuneration of employees. Supplements to wages and salaries consist of employer contributions for social insurance and employer payments (including payments in kind) to private pension and profit-sharing plans, group health and life insurance plans, privately administered workers' compensation plans.

IPUEN3111M000000000.title: Total Factor Productivity for Manufacturing: Animal Food Manufacturing (NAICS 3111) in the United States
IPUEN3111M000000000.notes: Total factor productivity is the efficiency at which combined inputs are used to produce output of goods and services. The total factor productivity indexes do not measure the specific contributions of capital, labor, and intermediate inputs. Rather, they reflect the joint influences on economic growth of a number of factors that are not specifically accounted for on the input side, including technological change, returns to scale, improved skills of the workforce, better management techniques, or other efficiency improvements.

IPUEN3113U110000000.title: Labor Compensation for Manufacturing: Sugar and Confectionery Product Manufacturing (NAICS 3113) in the United States

Supplemental payments include both legally required expenditures and payments for voluntary programs. The legally required portion consists primarily of federal old age and survivors’ insurance, unemployment compensation, and workers’ compensation. Payments for voluntary programs include all programs not specifically required by legislation, such as the employer portion of private health insurance and pension plans.

Wage and salary accruals consist of the monetary remuneration of employees. Supplements to wages and salaries consist of employer contributions for social insurance and employer payments (including payments in kind) to private pension and profit-sharing plans, group health and life insurance plans, privately administered workers' compensation plans.

IPUEN3116L020000000.title: Labor Compensation for Manufacturing: Animal Slaughtering and Processing (NAICS 3116) in the United States
IPUEN3116L020000000.notes: Labor compensation, defined as payroll plus supplemental payments, is a measure of the cost to the employer of securing the services of labor. Supplemental payments include both legally required expenditures and payments for voluntary programs. Payments for voluntary programs include all programs not specifically required by legislation, such as the employer portion of private health insurance and pension plans.

IPUEN3121P031000000.notes: Intermediate inputs share is the proportion of the total dollar value to produce output of goods and services attributed to use of intermediate inputs (energy, materials, and services).

IPUEN3121P060000000.title: Intermediate Inputs Intensity for Manufacturing: Beverage Manufacturing (NAICS 3121) in the United States
IPUEN3121P060000000.notes: Intermediate inputs intensity is the ratio of the amount of intermediate inputs used relative to the amount of labor hours used to produce output of goods and services.

IPUEN3121P061000000.title: Intermediate Inputs Intensity for Manufacturing: Beverage Manufacturing (NAICS 3121) in the United States
IPUEN3121P061000000.notes: Intermediate inputs intensity is the ratio of the amount of intermediate inputs used relative to the amount of labor hours used to produce output of goods and services.

IPUEN3121P070000000.title: Contribution of Intermediate Inputs Intensity to Labor Productivity for Manufacturing: Beverage Manufacturing (NAICS 3121) in the United States

IPUEN3121U100000000.title: Unit Labor Costs for Manufacturing: Beverage Manufacturing (NAICS 3121) in the United States
IPUEN3121U100000000.notes: Unit labor costs represent the cost of labor required to produce one unit of output. The unit labor cost indexes are computed by dividing an index of nominal industry labor compensation by an index of real industry output.

IPUEN3121U101000000.title: Unit Labor Costs for Manufacturing: Beverage Manufacturing (NAICS 3121) in the United States
IPUEN3121U101000000.notes: Unit labor costs represent the cost of labor required to produce one unit of output. The unit labor cost indexes are computed by dividing an index of nominal industry labor compensation by an index of real industry output.

IPUEN3121U110000000.title: Labor Compensation for Manufacturing: Beverage Manufacturing (NAICS 3121) in the United States
IPUEN3121U110000000.notes: Labor compensation, defined as payroll plus supplemental payments, is a measure of the cost to the employer of securing the services of labor. Payroll includes salaries, wages, commissions, dismissal pay, bonuses, vacation and sick leave pay, and compensation in kind. Supplemental payments include both legally required expenditures and payments for voluntary programs. The legally required portion consists primarily of federal old age and survivors’ insurance, unemployment compensation, and workers’ compensation. Payments for voluntary programs include all programs not specifically required by legislation, such as the employer portion of private health insurance and pension plans.

IPUEN3121U120000000.title: Hourly Compensation for Manufacturing: Beverage Manufacturing (NAICS 3121) in the United States
IPUEN3121U120000000.notes: Hourly compensation is the sum of wage and salary accruals and supplements to wages and salaries per hour of labor services used to produce output. Wage and salary accruals consist of the monetary remuneration of employees. Supplements to wages and salaries consist of employer contributions for social insurance and employer payments (including payments in kind) to private pension and profit-sharing plans, group health and life insurance plans, privately administered workers' compensation plans.

IPUEN31141L020000000.title: Labor Compensation for Manufacturing: Frozen Food Manufacturing (NAICS 31141) in the United States
IPUEN31141L020000000.notes: Labor compensation, defined as payroll plus supplemental payments, is a measure of the cost to the employer of securing the services of labor. Payroll includes salaries, wages, commissions, dismissal pay, bonuses, vacation and sick leave pay, and compensation in kind. Supplemental payments include both legally required expenditures and payments for voluntary programs. The legally required portion consists primarily of federal old age and survivors’ insurance, unemployment compensation, and workers’ compensation. Payments for voluntary programs include all programs not specifically required by legislation, such as the employer portion of private health insurance and pension plans.

IPUEN31161U110000000.title: Labor Compensation for Manufacturing: Animal Slaughtering and Processing (NAICS 31161) in the United States
IPUEN31161U110000000.notes: Labor compensation, defined as payroll plus supplemental payments, is a measure of the cost to the employer of securing the services of labor. Payroll includes salaries, wages, commissions, dismissal pay, bonuses, vacation and sick leave pay, and compensation in kind. Supplemental payments include both legally required expenditures and payments for voluntary programs. The legally required portion consists primarily of federal old age and survivors’ insurance, unemployment compensation, and workers’ compensation. Payments for voluntary programs include all programs not specifically required by legislation, such as the employer portion of private health insurance and pension plans.

IPUEN31161U120000000.title: Hourly Compensation for Manufacturing: Animal Slaughtering and Processing (NAICS 31161) in the United States
IPUEN31161U120000000.notes: Hourly compensation is the sum of wage and salary accruals and supplements to wages and salaries per hour of labor services used to produce output. Wage and salary accruals consist of the monetary remuneration of employees. Supplements to wages and salaries consist of employer contributions for social insurance and employer payments (including payments in kind) to private pension and profit-sharing plans, group health and life insurance plans, privately administered workers' compensation plans.

IPUEN312230L020000000.title: Labor Compensation for Manufacturing: Tobacco Manufacturing (NAICS 312230) in the United States
IPUEN312230L020000000.notes: Labor compensation, defined as payroll plus supplemental payments, is a measure of the cost to the employer of securing the services of labor.
